{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "A direct approach involves explicitly requesting the LLM in the prompt to generate test cases satisfying specific graph-theoretic coverage criteria (e.g., node coverage, edge coverage, or path coverage), although experiments indicate that LLMs struggle to fully satisfy complex path coverage requirements [92].",
    "Conversely, frameworks such as SymPrompt [118] and PALM [30] leverage static analysis to decompose methods into their fundamental execution paths.",
    "For each identified path, conditional statements controlling the execution flow are extracted as explicit constraints and integrated into the prompt, instructing the LLM to generate specific inputs that traverse that exact path.",
    "Advancing this domain, frameworks like LLM4TDG draw upon traditional constraint solving concepts, constructing formal constraint dependency graphs via static analysis and utilizing conflict analysis and backtracking mechanisms during iterative generation to more precisely guide LLMs in meeting complex testing requirements [86].",
    "This methodology transforms the vague task of increasing coverage into a series of concrete, constraint-solving sub-problems."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "A direct approach involves explicitly requesting the LLM in the prompt to generate test cases satisfying specific graph-theoretic coverage criteria (e.g., node coverage, edge coverage, or path coverage), although experiments indicate that LLMs struggle to fully satisfy complex path coverage requirements [92].",
